headline.main: FROM HAVANA.; ADDITIONAL CORRESPONDENCE. The Censulship--American Interests, &c.

docs.lead_paragraph: The following Letters from our regular correspondents were received by the Crescent City, but were crowded out of yesterday's TIMES by the press of other matter: Correspondence of the New-York Daily Times. HAVANA, Wednesday, Dec. 14, 1853.
docs.snippet: The following Letters from our regular correspondents were received by the Crescent City, but were crowded out of yesterday's TIMES by the press of other matter: Correspondence of the New-York Daily Times. HAVANA, Wednesday, Dec. 14, 1853.

docs.lead_paragraph: DEATHS.-The Health Officer reports 86 deaths for the week ending last Saturday: 53 females; 33 males. Of these deaths 13 were from consumption, and 11 stillborn.

headline.main: GRAND IRISH FESTIVAL.; BANQUET TO JOHN MITCHEL. SCENES AT THE BROADWAY THEATRE. SIX HUNDRED PERSONS AT DINNER. ADDRESS OF CHARLES O'CONOR, ESQ. SPEECH OF T. F. MEAGHER. Addresses of P. J. Smyth, Hon. John McKeon, Richard O'Gorman, John B. Dillon, Horace Greeley, and others.

docs.lead_paragraph: The grand Banquet in honor of JOHN MITCHELL, the Irish Patriot, took place last evening at the Broadway Theatre. The building was fitted up for the occasion, by covering the parqucite with a substantial flooring, upon which the tables were set. The boxes were reserved for the ladies, to whom two sea's were allotted for each ticket issued.

headline.main: OUR CARE OF EMIGRANTS.; The Philadelphia Delegation's Report.

docs.lead_paragraph: The delegation appointed by the EmigraRt Society of Philadelphia to inquire into the nature and operation of the Emigration Laws in this State have made an interesting report. The first part of it describes Ward's Island, its refuges and hospitals, nurseries, school-rooms and chapel. The order, decorum and propriety apparent there to all visitors, are much commended. headline.main: THE CATHOLICS AND PROTESTANTS.; PREACHING IN THE PUBLIC STREETS. Proclamation from the Mayor--Letter from Archbishop Hugffes. PROCLAMATION.

docs.lead_paragraph: It is the duty, as I trust it will be the pleasure, of every good citizen, to endeavor, by all lawful means, to preserve public peace. No man, governed by a proper respect for the welfare of our City, and the just rights of all who regard the supremacy of the laws, will directly or indirectly sanction or encourage any act tending to a violation of public order.
